00:04:35.610 --> 00:04:36.910
&gt;&gt; Michael Dirda: Thank you, David.

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:38.210
First of all, can you
all hear me all right?

00:04:38.210 --> 00:04:39.510
It's fine?

00:04:39.510 --> 00:04:41.810
Signal wildly if you can't.

00:04:43.210 --> 00:04:46.330
I was lucky enough to be
taught to read by my mother.

00:04:46.330 --> 00:04:49.890
After finishing the
dishes, she would plop

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:54.350
down on the dining room floor next
to the heat register and take me,

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:58.120
washed up, ready for
bed, onto her lap.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:01.690
There on the floor, she would
then open a tattered Golden Book

00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:03.910
and point with a fingertip --

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:09.970 position:56%
red and wrinkled by detergent in hot
water -- to the books first page.

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:11.270
"Look, Michael.

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:13.580
See the cute yellow chicky.

00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:19.010
Or the pokey little puppy
or the very naughty bunny."

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:23.620
As I snuggled there in my
mother's lap, feeling the warm air

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:25.890
of the furnace blowing on me,

00:05:25.890 --> 00:05:29.170
I would drift into a
contented sleepiness.

00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:31.830
Over time though, I
began to pay more

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:35.370
and more attention to
the books themselves.

00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:39.310
Probably because my beloved mother
seemed to derive so much pleasure

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:42.660
from the pictures and those
funny little squiggles.

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:47.030 position:56%
On the day I can no longer remember,

00:05:47.030 --> 00:05:50.550
I deduced like a four-year-old
Sherlock Holmes

00:05:50.550 --> 00:05:54.930
that those squiggles were
the letters -- C-A-T --

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:57.310
were pronounced cat and stood

00:05:57.310 --> 00:05:59.740
for the animal pictured
on the page above.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:04.830
When John Cole asked me to speak
at this afternoons ceremony

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:09.020
for the Literacy Awards, I began
to mull over what I might say.

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:14.480
We hear a great deal these
days about computer literacy,

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:18.390
but sometimes forget that
it is print literacy --

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:21.130
the ability to understand the
meaning of written words --

00:06:21.130 --> 00:06:27.800
which actually ushers most of us
into a world larger than ourselves.

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:30.010
Learning to read though
isn't at all intuitive.

00:06:30.010 --> 00:06:35.900
It takes hard work and persistence
on the part of parents, teachers,

00:06:35.900 --> 00:06:39.290
and organizations like
those we honor today.

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:42.400
Before a child can suddenly
achieve that eureka moment --

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:44.550
when the letters C-A-T --

00:06:44.550 --> 00:06:47.430
the picture of [inaudible]
animal playing a ball of yarn,

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:50.970
and the word "cat,"
all come together.

00:06:54.300 --> 00:06:57.520
Once these fundamental
interconnections are made though,

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:02.980
the truly life enhancing stages
of literacy actually begin.

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:06.230
These stages might be
labeled enchantment,

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:09.740
understanding, and power.

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:13.890
Our earliest reading is
the age of adventure.

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:15.510
We pick up books for excitement.

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:16.810
For wonder.

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:19.950
For the most basic enchantments
of plot and narrative.

00:07:19.950 --> 00:07:25.400
In my own generation, we discover
stories with irresistible titles

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:29.830
like " Danny Dunn and
the Anti-Gravity Paint,"

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:34.850
" Miss Pickerell Goes to Mars,"
and "The Boxcar Children."

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:37.790
We follow the never ending
battles between Uncle Scrooge

00:07:37.790 --> 00:07:40.350
and those dastardly Beagle Boys.

00:07:40.350 --> 00:07:43.630
Roar manically over joke
books with titles like

00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:46.030
"Yours Till Niagara Falls."

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:49.660
And eventually settled
down for a couple of years

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:54.830
with the endless adventures of
the Hardy Boys and Nancy Drew.

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:57.030
A little later perhaps,

00:07:57.030 --> 00:08:00.860
the librarian might suggest
a book intriguingly titled

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:03.470
"The Secret Garden."

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:07.800
Or at the local Salvation Army,
we might unearth an old paperback

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:11.180
of "Journey to the
Center of the Earth."

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:15.690
Or a cousin would lend us the
short stories of Edgar Allan Poe.

00:08:15.690 --> 00:08:20.220
In the 21st century, only
the particular titles might

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:21.520
be different.

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:24.670
Kids read now about Harry
Potter rather than Tom Swift,

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:29.550
Jr. But the overall
pattern remains the same.

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:33.710
Still, it pleases me to
know that Beverly Clearly,

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:37.000
whose Henry Huggins
books I eagerly searched

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.970
for in third grade,
will be 100 in April.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:49.060
As we all know, the true golden age
of reading is 12, or possibly 13.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:51.750
Does life get any better
than the dark

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:54.040
and stormy night we
first turn the pages

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:56.880
of "The Hound of the Baskervilles?"

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:00.620
On just such a night, I, myself
discovered the spectral hellhound

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:04.390
and learned of the curse laid
on the Baskerville family,

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:07.470
and listened as Dr. Mortimer
told of the recent death

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:09.120
of Sir Charles Baskerville.

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:16.970
Near the body, Mortimer informed
Sherlock Holmes, were footprints.

00:09:16.970 --> 00:09:23.080
The great detective immediately
asks, "A man's or a woman's?"

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:28.490
To which question, he receives what
is merely the most thrilling reply

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:31.150
in all of literature.

00:09:31.150 --> 00:09:35.260
"Mr. Holmes, they were the
footprints of a gigantic hound."

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:37.500
[ Laughter ]

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:41.980 position:56%
While enchantment and excitement are
important to any reader of any age,

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:45.260
there does come a time
when one begins to yearn

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:48.000
for more than just escape.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.270
As we grow older, we realize that
books don't only transport us

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:58.040
to fairy lands forlorn; they also
tell us about the world we live in.

00:09:58.040 --> 00:10:01.390
More and more, we read
to acquire knowledge.

00:10:01.390 --> 00:10:05.100
In school, we learn
through book about history.

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.170
We study key works of literature.

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:11.330
We review our Latin, or
French, or Arabic grammars.

00:10:11.330 --> 00:10:15.360
We prop up newspapers and
magazines -- or smart phones --

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:18.670
next to our bowl of breakfast
cereal to find out about politics

00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:23.540
and current affairs and
the latest baseball scores.

00:10:23.540 --> 00:10:27.820
Meanwhile, novels like "Pride
and Prejudice," and "The Red

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:31.000 position:56%
and The Black," teach us about love.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.190
Our horizons expand.

00:10:33.190 --> 00:10:36.150
We enter adulthood.

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:40.950
Through such youthful reading,
we grow in understanding,

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:43.880
acquiring a sense of what the world
is like and what we need to know

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:46.620
to navigate our way through it.

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:50.780
Gradually true, we discover
the third gift of literacy.

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:53.380
A consciousness of power.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:55.110
A confidence in ourselves.

00:10:55.110 --> 00:11:02.210 position:56%
When I was a boy, I devoured all the
self-help books of Dale Carnegie.

00:11:02.210 --> 00:11:06.680
Best known for " How to Win
Friends and Influence People."

00:11:06.680 --> 00:11:10.280
Throughout his work,
Carnegie repeatedly emphasized

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:14.630
that successful careers -- and to
some degree fulfilling lives --

00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:17.340
come more readily to those who
could speak and write well,

00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:21.880 position:56%
who know history, literature, and
the arts; who have read great books,

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:28.030
and have become, in the broadest
sense, educated men and women.

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:30.490
For all this popularity
among business people,

00:11:30.490 --> 00:11:34.460
Carnegie was a strong
advocate of the liberal arts.

00:11:34.460 --> 00:11:36.640
If you couldn't attend college --

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:40.960
and remember, he wrote during the
depression when many couldn't --

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:44.850
you could still go to the
library or the bookstore.

00:11:44.850 --> 00:11:48.970
You could teach yourself
if you knew how to read.

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:54.560
Such a peon to literacy may now
sound a little old fashioned

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:58.810
in our age of Facebook and Twitter,
but if you consult the memoirs

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:00.410
of poor kids who have made good,

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:03.350
you know that books
are always understood

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:06.420
as the key to their later success.

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:10.800
In prison, Malcolm X copied out
by hand the entire dictionary

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:14.810
so that he might improve his
vocabulary and better himself.

00:12:14.810 --> 00:12:18.140
Or recently, a son of a
working class Italian father

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:21.970
and a Mexican mother, Dana Gioia,
would -- through reading --

00:12:21.970 --> 00:12:24.990
rise to become the Chairman of the
National Endowment for the Arts

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:28.080
and one of the country's
finest poets.

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:32.630
Books and the knowledge found
in them enrich our souls, yes,

00:12:32.630 --> 00:12:38.530
but they also form the
foundations for consequential life.

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:42.600
The reader's journey then
leads from enchantment

00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:44.810
to understanding to power.

00:12:44.810 --> 00:12:49.060
But it all begins with learning
to recognize the letters

00:12:49.060 --> 00:12:51.700
of the alphabet on flashcards.

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:54.700
Then the simple words
in picture books.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:57.310
Literacy is the engine
that drives the world.

00:12:57.310 --> 00:13:02.160
The illiterate and alliterate
only drift aimlessly.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.970
Those who can read,
those who love to read,

00:13:04.970 --> 00:13:08.130
can go anywhere and do anything.

00:13:08.130 --> 00:13:11.970
Certainly, the three organizations
we honor today know this far better

00:13:11.970 --> 00:13:13.430
than I.

00:13:13.430 --> 00:13:16.670
They deserve our gratitude
and our applause.

00:13:16.670 --> 00:13:18.470
Thank you.

