00:45:14.080 --> 00:45:16.380
I want to share with you
a couple of the things

00:45:16.380 --> 00:45:19.120
that are keeping me awake.

00:45:19.120 --> 00:45:23.620
The first thing is the
sheer size of the problem.

00:45:23.620 --> 00:45:30.210
Our current educational crisis
is so vast, and our solutions,

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:33.740
they have to be equal
to that challenge.

00:45:33.740 --> 00:45:37.510
This last year, we
crossed a threshold --

00:45:37.510 --> 00:45:43.110
51 percent of kids in the United
States, in public schools --

00:45:43.110 --> 00:45:48.040
51 percent are from
low income families.

00:45:48.040 --> 00:45:54.270
The link between poverty and low
literacy is very well established.

00:45:54.270 --> 00:45:58.510
It shouldn't surprise any
of us to see that 80 percent

00:45:58.510 --> 00:46:04.370
of low income fourth graders are
not reading at proficient levels.

00:46:04.370 --> 00:46:09.800
And another way to say 80
percent is to say, almost none.

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:14.330
Almost none of those children
are confident readers.

00:46:14.330 --> 00:46:17.940
And so to shift a trend
of that size,

00:46:17.940 --> 00:46:21.750
we've got to build
large scale solutions.

00:46:21.750 --> 00:46:27.350
Solutions that will really produce
the dramatic results that we need.

00:46:27.350 --> 00:46:30.400
And that is what First
Book is all about.

00:46:30.400 --> 00:46:34.190
We have built dynamic models
that have delivered now more

00:46:34.190 --> 00:46:41.010
than 140 million books, and a large
and growing list of resources.

00:46:41.010 --> 00:46:42.310
And we're proud of that.

00:46:42.310 --> 00:46:44.400
And we're happy with that.

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:48.720
But we know every day, that
we have to grow faster.

00:46:48.720 --> 00:46:50.810
That we have to do more.

00:46:50.810 --> 00:46:55.630
And we have to do it at a rate
that's unprecedented if we're going

00:46:55.630 --> 00:46:59.420
to get ahead of the
wave that we see coming.

00:46:59.420 --> 00:47:04.200
The second thing that keeps
me awake at night is this.

00:47:04.200 --> 00:47:06.630
We need Gutenberg 2.0.

00:47:06.630 --> 00:47:08.920
And we need it now.

00:47:08.920 --> 00:47:11.940
We know from history
what access does

00:47:11.940 --> 00:47:15.230
to build an educated population.

00:47:15.230 --> 00:47:17.650
Gutenberg taught us that.

00:47:17.650 --> 00:47:19.550
The mass publishing industry

00:47:19.550 --> 00:47:26.340 position:56%
in the United States really ran full
throttle in about the mid-1800s.

00:47:26.340 --> 00:47:31.990
So it shouldn't surprise any
of us that after 150 years,

00:47:31.990 --> 00:47:36.350
that industry needs a major reset.

00:47:36.350 --> 00:47:39.340
The average price of
a premium picture book

00:47:39.340 --> 00:47:44.470
in the United States today is $18.

00:47:44.470 --> 00:47:50.950
$18 is a price point that excludes
everyone but the wealthiest five

00:47:50.950 --> 00:47:55.000
or maybe 10 percent of
the U.S. population.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:48:00.020
The publishers are not to blame
in this and anyone who works

00:48:00.020 --> 00:48:04.710
with publishers knows that they
are heart and soul in this battle.

00:48:04.710 --> 00:48:06.460
And they worked with us.

00:48:06.460 --> 00:48:11.200
They worked with many, many
other terrific organizations.

00:48:11.200 --> 00:48:15.090
But we also know -- all
of us in this room know --

00:48:15.090 --> 00:48:21.700
that publishing really holds the
intellectual life of our country.

00:48:21.700 --> 00:48:24.730
And it can't be designed in a way

00:48:24.730 --> 00:48:28.190
that it's limited to
the top five percent.

00:48:28.190 --> 00:48:33.630
At First Book, we're building
a brand new market at the base

00:48:33.630 --> 00:48:39.640
of the economic pyramid for books
and for educational resources.

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:44.760
Our market has grown more
than 30 percent every year.

00:48:44.760 --> 00:48:47.510
But we have to expand those efforts

00:48:47.510 --> 00:48:51.160
to reach every single
child in poverty.

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:55.340
To sustain and strengthen the
current publishing industry.

00:48:55.340 --> 00:48:59.270
And most importantly, to
make good on the promise

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:03.700
of equal education for
every single child.

00:49:03.700 --> 00:49:08.410
The third thing that keeps
me awake is that books need

00:49:08.410 --> 00:49:12.660
to be both affordable and relevant.

00:49:12.660 --> 00:49:15.600
People have been citing
a lack of relevancy.

00:49:15.600 --> 00:49:20.170
A lack of cultural diversity in
children's books for decades.

00:49:20.170 --> 00:49:25.420
And yet, in the last evaluation
by the University of Wisconsin,

00:49:25.420 --> 00:49:30.120
the percentage of non-white
children's authors is

00:49:30.120 --> 00:49:32.860
about eight percent.

00:49:32.860 --> 00:49:38.730
So there are wonderful books
being written by a huge range

00:49:38.730 --> 00:49:42.860
of wonderful authors,
but it's not enough.

00:49:42.860 --> 00:49:45.010
We're not moving it fast enough.

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:46.960
And we're not even close.

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:52.260
First Book's own research has
shown that over 90 percent

00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:56.150
of the educators we
serve have told us

00:49:56.150 --> 00:50:00.290
that their kids would be
more enthusiastic readers

00:50:00.290 --> 00:50:04.460
if the books reflected
their own lives.

00:50:04.460 --> 00:50:07.970
We've got to listen to
a voice that strong.

00:50:07.970 --> 00:50:11.140
We've got to listen
and we've got to act.

00:50:11.140 --> 00:50:15.990
Because between the high price of
books and the lack of relevancy,

00:50:15.990 --> 00:50:18.580
we're facing a really chasm.

00:50:18.580 --> 00:50:22.940
First Book has launched
something called Stories for All.

00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:25.780
And it's a program
that's revolutionary

00:50:25.780 --> 00:50:27.310
because it's market driven.

00:50:27.310 --> 00:50:32.720
And it is addressing this need but
we've got to amplify the results.

00:50:32.720 --> 00:50:35.490
We've got to move faster.

00:50:35.490 --> 00:50:40.860
Now, I can't close without
giving you some good news, right?

00:50:40.860 --> 00:50:44.940
Come on. We do know what works.

00:50:44.940 --> 00:50:46.520
We know what works.

00:50:46.520 --> 00:50:48.260
It's books.

00:50:48.260 --> 00:50:52.870
We hear from our network all of
the time, and we receive letters --

00:50:52.870 --> 00:50:56.490
