"Do you give those books away?"

00:58:45.430 --> 00:58:46.730
And they did what they could.

00:58:46.730 --> 00:58:49.370
But it's a very expensive
thing to manage.

00:58:49.370 --> 00:58:54.290
So we stepped into that space and
built the first system of its kind

00:58:54.290 --> 00:58:59.270
that now manages the lion's
share of contributed books

00:58:59.270 --> 00:59:00.570
from the publishing industry.

00:59:00.570 --> 00:59:01.870
That's the Book bank.

00:59:01.870 --> 00:59:03.220
And then there's the Marketplace.

00:59:03.220 --> 00:59:04.820
And these are very separate.

00:59:04.820 --> 00:59:10.210
The marketplace is when we buy
the inventory from the publishers.

00:59:10.210 --> 00:59:14.550
What we said to the publishers
in that instance is, "Look,

00:59:14.550 --> 00:59:17.210
you really are constrained --

00:59:17.210 --> 00:59:19.570
your market, the way it's
currently designed --

00:59:19.570 --> 00:59:24.300
the market for books is
constrained to the top veneer

00:59:24.300 --> 00:59:26.810
of socio-economic strata.

00:59:26.810 --> 00:59:29.360
And what we will do is we'll go out

00:59:29.360 --> 00:59:32.860
and aggregate the base
of the pyramid.

00:59:32.860 --> 00:59:35.500
So we will pay for aggregation.

00:59:35.500 --> 00:59:41.540
We will buy on a non-consignment,
a non-returnable basis.

00:59:41.540 --> 00:59:44.360
And that was music to
their ears of course.

00:59:44.360 --> 00:59:50.560
And then, we also said that they
wouldn't have to advertise to us.

00:59:50.560 --> 00:59:54.830
So we basically took away
all the risk from the market.

00:59:54.830 --> 00:59:57.700
And we took away a lot of the cost.

00:59:57.700 --> 01:00:01.870
And we said we expect your
prices to reflect the fact

01:00:01.870 --> 01:00:06.390
that we're building a new market
and that none of this risk is --

01:00:06.390 --> 01:00:08.940
or expenses any longer
on your plate.

01:00:08.940 --> 01:00:10.940
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So are
you bigger now in Washington

01:00:10.940 --> 01:00:13.660
than other cities or is
-- you're everywhere?

01:00:13.660 --> 01:00:17.590
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Nope, our network
-- we have an online system where,

01:00:17.590 --> 01:00:20.860
literally, anyone serving
children in need --

01:00:20.860 --> 01:00:26.300
zero to 18 years of age --
can sign up with us for free.

01:00:26.300 --> 01:00:31.460
Title I classrooms and schools,
anybody certain, you know,

01:00:31.460 --> 01:00:37.170
Head Starts, health care centers,
libraries, literally any place.

01:00:37.170 --> 01:00:41.150
They come on and they give us
their bonafide [inaudible] online.

01:00:41.150 --> 01:00:43.600
And that system is free.

01:00:43.600 --> 01:00:47.600
And once they're in --
once we've certified them,

01:00:47.600 --> 01:00:51.440
then they can have access to
both the book bank inventory --

01:00:51.440 --> 01:00:53.490
where they only pay for shipping --

01:00:53.490 --> 01:00:57.570
and the marketplace inventory
where the average price

01:00:57.570 --> 01:01:03.540
of a brand new paperback book,
including shipping, is $2.85.

01:01:03.540 --> 01:01:06.060
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So
what ages do you focus on?

01:01:06.060 --> 01:01:09.310
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Well, we
cover zero to eighteen.

01:01:09.310 --> 01:01:10.910
We're all the way up.

01:01:10.910 --> 01:01:13.650
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: And what about
adults who can't afford books?

01:01:13.650 --> 01:01:15.500
Have you gone into that area yet?

01:01:15.500 --> 01:01:16.800
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Well, we haven't.

01:01:16.800 --> 01:01:19.030
By the time, I mean,
we haven't overtly.

01:01:19.030 --> 01:01:21.490
By the time -- there are
a bunch of programs though

01:01:21.490 --> 01:01:27.940
where new moms will come
into the program to get books

01:01:27.940 --> 01:01:31.310
through their system to
read with their child.

01:01:31.310 --> 01:01:35.700
We also have a lot of books
that we specifically look

01:01:35.700 --> 01:01:42.600
for that are very high interest
in low level vocabulary to begin

01:01:42.600 --> 01:01:48.310 position:56%
to bring the older population -- the
older readers -- into the system.

01:01:48.310 --> 01:01:50.740
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So somebody
gets a book from your system.

01:01:50.740 --> 01:01:53.250
A child gets two or three
books and you have them,

01:01:53.250 --> 01:01:54.550
what do they do typically

01:01:54.550 --> 01:01:57.350
when they're done reading
them 20 or 30 or 40 times.

01:01:57.350 --> 01:01:59.980
Do they pass them along
or do they hold them,

01:01:59.980 --> 01:02:01.860
put them in their library,
what do they do with them?

01:02:01.860 --> 01:02:04.050
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: It's every
story you can imagine.

01:02:04.050 --> 01:02:07.210
So, you know, there are some
schools, some classrooms

01:02:07.210 --> 01:02:09.420
that build classroom
libraries with them.

01:02:09.420 --> 01:02:16.780
There are some families that -- you
saw them on Sally's presentation,

01:02:16.780 --> 01:02:18.660
you know, family libraries.

01:02:18.660 --> 01:02:22.340
And we know how important
that is for reading skills.

01:02:22.340 --> 01:02:25.070 position:56%
We know that having a family library

01:02:25.070 --> 01:02:29.410
of even 20 books has
an extraordinary impact

01:02:29.410 --> 01:02:31.350
on the academic achievement.

01:02:31.350 --> 01:02:33.460
So some of them stay
home with the kids,

01:02:33.460 --> 01:02:36.770
some of them get traded
around from kid to kid.

01:02:36.770 --> 01:02:38.070
It depends on the program.

01:02:38.070 --> 01:02:39.370
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: And
is there a difference

01:02:39.370 --> 01:02:42.600 position:56%
between whether a child likes a book
with a hard back or a soft back?

01:02:42.600 --> 01:02:43.900
Does it make a difference?

01:02:43.900 --> 01:02:45.540
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: I don't think
it makes a difference at all.

01:02:45.540 --> 01:02:46.840
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: Does
it make a difference --

01:02:46.840 --> 01:02:48.350
why do publishers still
publish a hard back?

01:02:48.350 --> 01:02:50.180
Because it's presumably
more expensive or --

01:02:50.180 --> 01:02:52.380
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: It's
very much more expansive.

01:02:52.380 --> 01:02:55.620
And I don't think it makes
a difference to the kid.

01:02:55.620 --> 01:02:58.600
I think that there are
a lot of reasons --

01:02:58.600 --> 01:03:01.590
people love the feeling
of hard back books.

01:03:01.590 --> 01:03:04.350
And it also, you know,
is a lovely thing

01:03:04.350 --> 01:03:06.240 position:56%
for a keepsake and things like that.

01:03:06.240 --> 01:03:09.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So a lot of
adults now are reading books online.

01:03:09.140 --> 01:03:10.440
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Yup.

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:11.740
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: And on
Kindles or other devices.

01:03:11.740 --> 01:03:13.050
Are children doing that yet?

01:03:13.050 --> 01:03:14.890
Do they have their own
kindles yet for children

01:03:14.890 --> 01:03:18.270
or they're still reading books
-- the kind of books you provide?

01:03:18.270 --> 01:03:20.220
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Well, I don't think

01:03:20.220 --> 01:03:26.060 position:56%
that the digital content space has
taken off anywhere nearly as quickly

01:03:26.060 --> 01:03:28.840
as the industry thought it might.

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:31.560
And it breaks down by age.

01:03:31.560 --> 01:03:37.180
Kids -- the older kids may not
have kindles but they certainly --

01:03:37.180 --> 01:03:42.560
there's a huge penetration of smart
phones and smart technology, right?

01:03:42.560 --> 01:03:48.940 position:56%
So those were actually working and
providing and increasing opportunity

01:03:48.940 --> 01:03:53.320
for digital content to
make that accessible

01:03:53.320 --> 01:03:54.990
through the First Book Marketplace.

01:03:54.990 --> 01:03:58.980
But littler kids, the
technology isn't really there.

01:03:58.980 --> 01:04:02.800
You know, because you
have to have a unit

01:04:02.800 --> 01:04:05.810
that is simultaneously
high quality enough --

01:04:05.810 --> 01:04:07.110
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: Right.

01:04:07.110 --> 01:04:09.380
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: That it
can capture the artwork,

01:04:09.380 --> 01:04:12.040
and it can also have grape juice
spilled on it and be dropped

01:04:12.040 --> 01:04:13.340
down a flight of steps, right?

01:04:13.340 --> 01:04:14.640
And so --

01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:15.940
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein:
Who does a better job

01:04:15.940 --> 01:04:17.310
of preparing children to read?

01:04:17.310 --> 01:04:20.060
Fathers or mothers
when they're reading?

01:04:20.060 --> 01:04:21.770
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Oh, man.

01:04:21.770 --> 01:04:23.070
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein:
When they're reading

01:04:23.070 --> 01:04:24.440
to their children, is
there a difference?

01:04:24.440 --> 01:04:25.890
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: No, there's not.

01:04:25.890 --> 01:04:28.280
You know, I think the --

01:04:28.280 --> 01:04:34.500
what we want is we want 24/7
surround sound for kids.

01:04:34.500 --> 01:04:35.920
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: And
if you don't have a parent,

01:04:35.920 --> 01:04:38.040
does it make a difference
for the child?

01:04:38.040 --> 01:04:40.080
Or who typically reads to
the children if, let's say,

01:04:40.080 --> 01:04:42.400
they don't have a parent or
they're one parent families.

01:04:42.400 --> 01:04:44.000
Is it a big difference?

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:46.190
Do you see a big difference in
their literacy capabilities --

01:04:46.190 --> 01:04:48.450
there's a one parent family?

01:04:48.450 --> 01:04:52.960
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: I think poverty
is the main indicator on that.

01:04:52.960 --> 01:04:58.670
It's when you've got caring adults,
that's the most important thing.

01:04:58.670 --> 01:05:00.180
That's the most important thing.

01:05:00.180 --> 01:05:04.340 position:56%
And when they're reading in the life
of a child, that's a power tool.

01:05:04.340 --> 01:05:05.640
That's tremendous.

01:05:05.640 --> 01:05:11.100
I will tell you, quickly, that
I've seen just recently some

01:05:11.100 --> 01:05:15.520
extraordinary programs where
they are bringing older kids

01:05:15.520 --> 01:05:20.440
who are struggling with reading
themselves in to read and tutor

01:05:20.440 --> 01:05:23.480
with younger kids in
the same school.

01:05:23.480 --> 01:05:28.960
And the impact metrics
on that is breathtaking.

01:05:28.960 --> 01:05:30.740
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So I
suppose President Obama called you

01:05:30.740 --> 01:05:32.040
up and said, "I heard --

01:05:32.040 --> 01:05:33.340
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: He
does all the time.

01:05:33.340 --> 01:05:34.640
[ Laughter ]

01:05:34.640 --> 01:05:35.940
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: He'd
say you've done a great job.

01:05:35.940 --> 01:05:37.240
I've heard about this award.

01:05:37.240 --> 01:05:38.540
I've heard about the organization.

01:05:38.540 --> 01:05:40.500
I'll give you a 100
million dollars --

01:05:40.500 --> 01:05:42.850
okay, I'll give you a billion
dollars, what would you do

01:05:42.850 --> 01:05:44.700
to improve the literacy
in the United States

01:05:44.700 --> 01:05:46.180
with 100 million or
a billion dollars?

01:05:46.180 --> 01:05:47.480
What would you do with that?

01:05:47.480 --> 01:05:49.230
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Well, the first
thing I would do is I'd make sure

01:05:49.230 --> 01:05:52.140
every teacher, every educator,

01:05:52.140 --> 01:05:57.120
every preschool setting had
every resource they need.

01:05:57.120 --> 01:06:00.310
Right now, what we
have is an army --

01:06:00.310 --> 01:06:02.450
forgive me for the
military reference --

01:06:02.450 --> 01:06:08.590 position:56%
but we have an army with no supply
-- with an inadequate supply system.

01:06:08.590 --> 01:06:12.810
And so I think that's the magic
of what first book is building.

01:06:12.810 --> 01:06:17.890
And with infinite funding
or nearly infinite funding,

01:06:17.890 --> 01:06:22.740
our ability to upgrade IT
systems, to market and make sure

01:06:22.740 --> 01:06:26.960
that every eligible
teacher is in the system

01:06:26.960 --> 01:06:28.800
and receiving the benefits --

01:06:28.800 --> 01:06:35.900
you can't imagine what pent
up heroes there are out there.

01:06:35.900 --> 01:06:40.170
Teachers go into teaching,
people are working at Head Start

01:06:40.170 --> 01:06:43.800
and they've all got ideas
about what they want to do

01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:45.510
with the kids in their program.

01:06:45.510 --> 01:06:50.950
And so when they get resources,
the lid blows off the place.

01:06:50.950 --> 01:06:52.250
It's really inspiring.

01:06:52.250 --> 01:06:53.550
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So have
