And you're very happy
with what you've done?

01:07:58.240 --> 01:08:00.700
If you could do it all over again,
what would you do differently?

01:08:00.700 --> 01:08:03.070
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: You know, I
don't have a single regret.

01:08:03.070 --> 01:08:05.370
I feel like the luckiest
person in the world.

01:08:05.370 --> 01:08:06.670
I really do.

01:08:06.670 --> 01:08:12.620 position:56%
Because I feel like I spent a number
of years in training as a lawyer.

01:08:12.620 --> 01:08:15.890
And then a number of years
working as a lawyer at the elbow

01:08:15.890 --> 01:08:22.540
of brilliantly talented lawyers
who were able to sharpen my skills

01:08:22.540 --> 01:08:27.350
and my analytical reasoning
and my business skills.

01:08:27.350 --> 01:08:34.940 position:56%
And I've been able to pivot and turn
and apply that to something that --

01:08:34.940 --> 01:08:38.180
it's tremendously meaningful to me.

01:08:38.180 --> 01:08:41.450
And I get to work with
extraordinary people.

01:08:41.450 --> 01:08:42.750
Some of whom are sitting here.

01:08:42.750 --> 01:08:45.100
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein: So would
you recommend to your children

01:08:45.100 --> 01:08:46.690
that they go to law school?

01:08:46.690 --> 01:08:49.080
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: Yeah,
actually, I would recommend it.

01:08:49.080 --> 01:08:50.380
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein:
But not practice law?

01:08:50.380 --> 01:08:51.680
&gt;&gt; Kyle Zimmer: I think it's --

01:08:51.680 --> 01:08:52.980
certainly not practi-,
no, I'm teasing.

01:08:52.980 --> 01:08:55.940
You know, I think it's
great training.

01:08:55.940 --> 01:09:04.420
I think it made me far more capable
